</span></span></span></code></div></div></pre>
<p data-start="602" data-end="635"><strong data-start="602" data-end="635">This is your Ubuntu terminal.</strong></p>
<ol start="2" data-start="637" data-end="703">
<li data-start="637" data-end="703">
<p data-start="640" data-end="703"><strong data-start="640" data-end="703">Alternatively, you can use it directly from Windows search:</strong></p>
</li>
</ol>
<ul data-start="704" data-end="754">
<li data-start="704" data-end="754">
<p data-start="706" data-end="754">Press <code data-start="712" data-end="725">Windows key</code>, type <strong data-start="732" data-end="744">“Ubuntu”</strong>, open it.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="756" data-end="759">
<h2 data-start="761" data-end="808">✅ <strong data-start="766" data-end="808">To use Ubuntu inside VS Code terminal:</strong></h2>
<h3 data-start="810" data-end="831">1️⃣ Open VS Code.</h3>
<h3 data-start="832" data-end="876">2️⃣ Press <code data-start="846" data-end="856">Ctrl + ~</code> → to open terminal.</h3>
<h3 data-start="877" data-end="925">3️⃣ If it still opens PowerShell, change it:</h3>
<ul data-start="926" data-end="1108">
<li data-start="926" data-end="1027">
<p data-start="928" data-end="1027">Click the dropdown arrow <code data-start="953" data-end="956">˅</code> beside the terminal tab → <strong data-start="983" data-end="1009">Select Default Profile</strong> → <strong data-start="1012" data-end="1022">Ubuntu</strong>.<br>
OR:</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1028" data-end="1108">
<p data-start="1030" data-end="1108">Go to <strong data-start="1036" data-end="1107">File → Preferences → Settings → Terminal → Default Profile → Ubuntu</strong>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p data-start="1110" data-end="1153">✅ Now your VS Code terminal will also show:</p>
